WEATHER_CONCERNS_NARR: today will bring another near critical fire weather day as hot  dry and breezy conditions remain the key weather elements on the incident.  although fire weather parameters will not reach levels achieved on thursday  it still warrants concern. smoke coverage will once again be a significant factor in determining how high temperatures soar and how low humidity dips. a rather complex wind pattern remains present with breezy northwest winds in the afternoon and evening being the noteworthy feature. beyond friday  a slight cooling trend is expected as we push into next week.

REMARKS: dozers are currently constructing contingency line to contain the slopover south of primary containment lines in the kirby peak area  where challenging terrain and heavy fuels may necessitate the use of indirect attack and firing operations in some locations. this slopover resulted in evacuation orders for approximately 5 000 residents. see box 30 for specifics.   there is a public meeting scheduled in groveland on friday.   this area has a history of producing very rapid rates of spread when fire comes into alignment with wind and topography under northwestern wind flow. in 1961 the harlow fire burned 20 000 acres in 2 hours in this area. southeastern fire spread has moved the ferguson fire into similar fuels and topography in this area. until the cedar fire in 2003  the harlow fire held the record for the most acres burned in a single shift.  the incident base for the ferguson fire is at the ahwahnee hills regional park. additional camps have been established at badger pass and drew meadows.  operations are being conducted under a joint delegation of authority from the sierra national forest  yosemite national park and the stanislaus national forest.

REMARKS: crews and dozers are currently constructing contingency line to contain the slopover south of primary containment lines in the kirby peak area  where challenging terrain and heavy fuels may necessitate the use of indirect attack and firing operations in some locations. this slopover resulted in evacuation orders for approximately 5 000 residents. see box 30 for specifics.   there is a public meeting scheduled in groveland on friday.   this area has a history of producing very rapid rates of spread when fire comes into alignment with wind and topography under northwestern wind flow. in 1961 the harlow fire burned 20 000 acres in 2 hours in this area. southeastern fire spread has moved the ferguson fire into similar fuels and topography in this area. until the cedar fire in 2003  the harlow fire held the record for the most acres burned in a single shift.  the incident base for the ferguson fire is at the ahwahnee hills regional park. additional camps have been established at badger pass and drew meadows.  operations are being conducted under a joint delegation of authority from the sierra national forest  yosemite national park and the stanislaus national forest.
